body:
**Describe the bug**
ORT computes min incorrectly for negative fp16 values in opsets 12 and 13.  It says the min of 2 and -5 is 2.

**Urgency**
Bug is present in production version of ORT.  May cause existing models to fail.

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): **Windows 10**
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): PyPI
- ONNX Runtime version: **1.6.0**
- Python version: 3.8

**To Reproduce**
```
from onnx import helper
from onnx.onnx_pb import TensorProto
import onnxruntime as ort
import numpy as np

node1 = helper.make_node("Min", ["X", "Y"], ["Z"], name="trans")

graph = helper.make_graph(
    [node1],
    "min_graph",
    [
        helper.make_tensor_value_info("X", TensorProto.FLOAT16, [3]), 
        helper.make_tensor_value_info("Y", TensorProto.FLOAT16, [3])
    ],
    [helper.make_tensor_value_info("Z", TensorProto.FLOAT16, [3])],
)

model_proto = helper.make_model(graph)

sess = ort.InferenceSession(model_proto.SerializeToString())
x_val = [1, 2, -3]
y_val = [4, -5, -6]
res = sess.run(["Z"], {"X": np.array(x_val, dtype=np.float16), "Y": np.array(y_val, dtype=np.float16)})
print(res[0])
# Should be [1, -5, -6] but is [1, 2, -3]
```

title: Opset12+fp16 runs much slower than opset10/opset11+fp16 in V100 gpu, only 1/88
body:
**Describe the bug**
Hi ort team,

We are using ORT to serve our models. 
Our models are torch models. We will first convert torch models to ONNX models using ```torch.onnx.export(opset_version=x)``` (OpsetX+fp32 for short), then convert the ONNX models to fp16 (OpsetX+fp16 for short) with [onnxconverter-common](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxconverter-common/blob/master/onnxconverter_common/float16.py) to further improve the speed.
It works fine for Opset10+fp16 and Opset11+fp16. However, when we switched to Opset12+fp16, the throughput didn't increase but decreased a lot. It happens on lots of models. 
I provided an example below. In this example, those four models are converted from the same torch model. From the throughput result, 3 models work fine, only Opset12+fp16 has a huge performance issue, which is only about 1/88 of Opset11+fp16. We would like to ask your help to figure out why. Thanks.

| Model Info  | Throughput(samples/s/gpu) |
| ------------- | ------------- |
| Opset11, fp32, batch_size=32 | 4823.70 |
| Opset11, fp16, batch_size=32 | 15256.17  |
| Opset12, fp32, batch_size=32  | 4834.07  |
| Opset12, fp16, batch_size=32  | **172.71**|

Note:
1. Before reporting this issue to ORT, we have reached to onnxconverter-common team. They didn't see any issue on the fp16 conversion code. And the output results of those models are correct. 
2. We also tested on opset10, with or without fp16, their throughputs are similar as opset11. The only issue is the speed of Opset12+fp16.
3. **It is not just this model has issue, several other models (transformers-based models) have performance issue on Opset12+fp16 too.**


**Urgency**
We are running an ONNX inference platform for Microsoft ads users. This is not a blocking issue, we are asking our users to try opset10 or opset11 for their models as an alternative solution. However, as opset12 is newer, we expect opset12 should perform better, not worse.

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): Ubuntu 18.04.2 LTS
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): source
- ONNX Runtime version: 1.5.1
- Python version: 3.6.8
- Visual Studio version (if applicable): N/A
- GCC/Compiler version (if compiling from source): gcc/g++ 7.4.0
- CUDA/cuDNN version: Cuda compilation tools, release 10.1, V10.1.168
- GPU model and memory: V100, 16GB. AML SKU: Standard_ND40s_v2 (V100*8, 16GB)

**To Reproduce**
- Describe steps/code to reproduce the behavior.

Below is the code I used to test the throughputs of these models. You can simply change the model name in ```model_path``` and test their throughputs.
```python
import onnx
import onnxruntime as ort
import numpy as np
import time
import datetime

model_path = "./opset11_fp32.onnx"
batch_size = 32

sess_options = ort.SessionOptions()
sess_options.graph_optimization_level = ort.GraphOptimizationLevel.ORT_ENABLE_ALL
sess_options.intra_op_num_threads = 0
ort_sess = ort.InferenceSession(model_path, sess_options)


qseq_value_list=list()
qmask_value_list=list()
num_samples = 0
with open("input.tsv", "r") as fin:
    for line in fin:
        uid, label, inputTensors= line.strip().split("\t")
        qseq, qmask = inputTensors.split(";")
        qseq_value = np.fromstring(qseq.split("=")[1], dtype=np.int64, sep=' ')
        qmask_value = np.fromstring(qmask.split("=")[1], dtype=np.int64, sep=' ')
        qseq_value_list.append(qseq_value)
        qmask_value_list.append(qmask_value)
        num_samples += 1

qseq_value_list = np.array(qseq_value_list)
qmask_value_list = np.array(qmask_value_list)

num_samples = num_samples//batch_size*batch_size
total_samples = 0
feed_dict = {}
processed_time = 0
for batch_idx in range(0, num_samples, batch_size):
    feed_dict["qseq"] = qseq_value_list[batch_idx:batch_idx+batch_size]
    feed_dict["qmask"] = qmask_value_list[batch_idx:batch_idx+batch_size]
    total_samples += batch_size
    start = time.time()
    _output_tensors = ort_sess.run(["qvec"], feed_dict)
    processed_time += time.time() - start
    if (batch_idx//batch_size)%10==0:
        print(datetime.datetime.now().strftime("%H:%M:%S"), f"{batch_idx//batch_size} batches processed, total batches: {num_samples//batch_size}")
        #if batch_idx//batch_size==100:
        #    break
print(f"It processed {total_samples} samples using {processed_time} seconds, avg througput is {total_samples/processed_time} samples/s.")
```

- Attach the ONNX model to the issue (where applicable) to expedite investigation.
https://www.dropbox.com/s/4vsj2p29j69w89i/TwinBertTest.zip?dl=0

It contains 6 files:
1. inferenceTest.py: test code
2. input.tsv: input data
3. opset11_fp32.onnx: convert with opset11
4. opset11_fp16.onnx: convert opset11_fp32.onnx to fp16
5. opset12_fp32.onnx: convert with opset12
6. opset12_fp16.onnx: convert opset12_fp32.onnx to fp16

**Expected behavior**
I expect the throughput of **opset12_fp16.onnx** should be at least similar as **opset11_fp16.onnx**

title: Fix Min/Max CPU kernels for float16 type
body:
**Description**: The `Min` and `Max` CPU kernels claim support for float16 type yet they aren't handled properly in the implementation. This change fixes that.

Usually CPU kernels don't support float16 type and rely on the InsertCastTransformer to cast to/from float and perform the operation(s) itself in float. But, it feels wrong to "de-register" support for float16 in these CPU kernels. Given that they need to (or claim that they support float16), they need to provide the right results

**Motivation and Context**
Fixes https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/6153

title: build.py ImportError: wrong 'util' imported
body:
```
 Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "./tools/ci_build/build.py", line 24, in <module>
    from util import run  # noqa: E402
ImportError: cannot import name 'run' from 'util' (/usr/local/lib/python3.7/site-packages/util.py)
```

**Describe the bug**
The `tools/ci_build/build.py` script can import the wrong `util` library because `sys.path.**append**` can put the util library path after python site-packages path.

On my system, I already have python's site-packages on my path, so after 
`sys.path.append(os.path.join(REPO_DIR, "tools", "python"))`
my `sys.path` is  
`'[/usr/local/lib/python3.7/site-packages', '/home/mgoin/code/onnx-runtime/tools/python']`

**Urgency**
Bug is present in production version of ORT. May cause build and testing environments to fail depending on `sys.path` setup.

**System information**
OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): Linux 4.19.88-1-MANJARO
ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): source
ONNX Runtime version: rel-1.6.0
Python version: 3.7

**Temporary Fix**
You can get past this issue by replacing 
`sys.path.append(os.path.join(REPO_DIR, "tools", "python"))` 
with 
`sys.path.insert(0, os.path.join(REPO_DIR, "tools", "python"))` 

This ensures that onnxruntime's util library will always be first in `sys.path`

https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/111ac299cc26d0b7dfca68e500855e927653c157/tools/ci_build/build.py#L18-L24

title: Support MLFloat16 type in Pow opset-12 CUDA kernel
body:
**Description**: Investigating a perf issue where-in a half-precision opset-11 model is substantially faster than a half-precision opset-12 model. Tracked it down to the fact the opset-12 CUDA Pow kernel didn't support the `MLFloat16` type. The class backing the kernel actually supports `MLFloat16` and so it just needed adding to the list of types supported by the kernel.
Used the `onnxruntime_perf_test` executable and verified that the performance of both the opset-11 and opset-12 models are now on par with this change.  

**Motivation and Context**
Resolves https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/6173 (used the model attached in the issue for debugging)

title: MLAS: handle MlasGemm(M/N/K==0) cases
body:
**Description**: Update the floating point GEMM routines to handle the case where any of M/N/K are zero.

**Motivation and Context**
This fixes the crash from #6232 where one of the GEMM parameters was zero inside the LSTM op. Many ops were already bailing out early if the output tensor size was zero, but this should be handled more robustly inside MLAS.

The DGEMM code has been resynchronized with the SGEMM code (this code still needs to be templated to avoid some of the code duplication).

The unit test has been updated to exercise the M/N/K is zero path.

title: model parallel refinement
body:
**Description**: 
1.  Do model parallel partition after other transformations are done. 
2.  Consolidate different graph matching logics within same topological sort loop. This is needed for subsequent All Reduce pair guarantee change. 

**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?

Previously, model parallel partition is done in different optimizer iterations for different layers. This is because, the partition depends on graph matching, which is affected by other optimizer for some layers. So we move the model parallel partition as a separate graph transformation step after all others are done. 

- If it fixes an open issue, please link to the issue here.

title: Fix Linux/Mac error message on input type mismatch
body:
**Description**: The name() method of `type_info` class is implementation dependent and may return a mangled non-human readable string which may have to be unmangled (see https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/4787 to see how gcc's stdlib implementation returns name of type_info). Currently this mangled string bubbles all the way up to the users on type mis-match. AFAIK - only MSVC's implementation seems human readable. This change tries to remedy this unfriendly error message on some platforms.

**Motivation and Context**
Takeaway from https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/4787
